{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox video game | title = Okhlos | image = Okhlos logo.png | caption = Logo of ''Okhlos'' | developer = [[Coffee Powered Machine]] | publisher = [[Devolver Digital]] | engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]] | platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]] | released = {{Video game release|WW|18 August 2016}} | genre = [[Action game|Action]], [[roguelike]] | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]] | designer = {{Unbulleted list | Sebastián Gioseffi | Roque Rey Ordoñez }} | programmer = Sebastián Gioseffi | artist = Roque Rey Ordoñez | writer = {{Unbulleted list | Roque Rey Ordoñez | Sebastián Gioseffi }} | composer = Gordon "A Shell in the Pit" McGladdery }}
'''''Okhlos''''' (stylized as '''''OKHLOS''''') is an [[Action game|action]] [[roguelike]] [[video game]] developed by [[Argentina]]-based independent video game developer [[Coffee Powered Machine]] and published by [[Devolver Digital]]. It was released on 18 August 2016.
== Plot == ''Okhlos'' is set in [[ancient Greece]], where the land is ruled by the [[Olympian gods]], who are highly praised by the people.<ref name="KS: Mob mentality">{{cite web | url = http://killscreendaily.com/articles/okhlos-turns-ancient-greece-explore-phenomenon-mob-mentality/ | title = Okhlos turns to Ancient Greece to explore the phenomenon of mob mentality | last = Rudin | first = David | date = 14 May 2015 | website = [[Kill Screen]] | publisher = [[Kill Screen Media]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> However, the game's [[protagonist]], an unnamed philosopher, is critical about their behaviour, as they show no signs of interest in the human [[well-being]].<ref name="RPS: Greek Pikmin">{{cite web | url = http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/01/20/mob-rules-okhlos-is-insane-ancient-greek-pikmin/ | title = Mob Rules: Okhlos Is Insane Ancient Greek Pikmin | last = Grayson | first = Nathan | date = 20 January 2014 | website = [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> But, when the philosopher suddenly witnesses, how [[the School of Athens]] is bruised down by one of the god's foot, killing everyone inside, he decides to take action.<ref name="Poly: Mob justice">{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2015/8/29/9225083/mob-justice-is-the-central-philosophy-of-okhlos | title = Mob justice is the central philosophy of Okhlos | last = Campbell | first = Collin | date = 29 August 2015 | website = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | publisher = [[Vox Media]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> Going from city to city, he convinces the people that the gods are no good for mankind, as they turn people into animals, impregnate women and kill innocents, and recruits them to form a giant mob.<ref name="Poly: Mob justice" /> As the mob grows, the philosopher continues executing his plan to overthrow the gods, kill their minions, and form an [[ochlocracy]], while his mob destroys everything standing in their way.<ref name="RPS: Greek Pikmin" />
== Gameplay == ''Okhlos'' is often compared to ''[[Pikmin]]'', as the player rules over a huge mob, directing it to go to the commanded spots,<ref name="Kotaku: Imagine Pikmin">{{cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/imagine-pikmin-but-with-greek-philosophers-1510025170 | title = Imagine ''Pikmin'', But With Greek Philosophers | last = Person | first = Chris | date = 27 January 2014 | website = [[Kotaku]] | publisher = [[Gawker Media]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> in combination with ''[[Katamari]]'' for the fast-paced action.<ref name="Destructoid: Okhlos has Katamari vibes">{{cite web | url = http://www.destructoid.com/devolver-digital-s-okhlos-has-katamari-vibes-with-a-mob-twist-340722.phtml | title = Devolver Digital's Okhlos has Katamari vibes with a mob twist | last = Carter | first = Chris | date = 11 February 2016 | website = [[Destructoid]] | publisher = [[ModernMethod]] | accessdate = 11 February 2016}}</ref> Upon touching, the mob will automatically start tearing down buildings, attack enemies or recruit new people.<ref name="Poly: Mob justice" /> Additionally, the player can make the mob block or spread around the city they are in to protect the player from enemies or hazards.<ref name="KS: Mob mentality" /> The game's eight worlds are [[Procedural generation|procedurally generated]], each featuring different hazards and enemies to face.<ref name="PD: All hail the mob">{{cite web | url = https://www.pixeldynamo.com/news/gaming/2015/05/14/63811/hail-mob-okhlos-seeks-greenlight-approval-steam/ | title = All hail the mob: Okhlos seeks Greenlight approval on Steam | last = Pursaill | first = James | date = 14 May 2015 | website = [[Pixel Dynamo]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> Every city includes shops, in which the player may buy upgrades for individual units of the mob, or increase the number of people able to join it.<ref name="YT: Cannata">{{cite AV media | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=82FMDitsG0c | title = OKHLOS: Wreak Havoc through Ancient Greece! PAX 2015 | last = Cannata | first = Jeff | date = 31 August 2015 | website = [[YouTube]] | publisher = [[Google]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> To that, the player may, in the shops, also trade units for famous Greek philosophers and heroes, such as [[Aristotle]] and [[Heracles]].<ref name="IGM: BIG preview">{{cite web | url = http://indiegamemag.com/big-festival-preview-okhlos/ | title = BIG Festival Preview - Okhlos | last = Viana | first = Bhernardo | date = 8 July 2015 | website = [[Indie Game Magazine]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> Over the course of the game, the player will face and battle all of the [[Twelve Olympians]], as well as randomly encountering other major enemies, like the [[Oracle of Delphi]] or the [[Minotaur]].<ref name="PD: All hail the mob" /> In case the player dies, he will take over one of the philosophers from the mob, except if there is no philosophers left, which will cause the player to lose.<ref name="IGM: BIG preview" />
== Development == Development on ''Okhlos'' started in November 2012, after Argentinian indie studio Coffee Powered Machine released the ''Enhanced Edition'' of their previous title, ''[[Gravity Fleet]]'', to the [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] on 13 November 2012.<ref name="IGN: App Store Update">{{cite web | url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/11/13/app-store-update-november-13 | title = App Store Update: November 13 | last = Thomas | first = Lucas M. | date = 13 November 2012 | website = [[IGN]] | publisher = [[IGN Entertainment]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> The team decided to create a game about an angry mob in ancient Greece, consisting of mythological heroes, that is fighting the Olympian gods.<ref name="TechRaptor: Interview">{{cite web | url = http://techraptor.net/content/mob-rules-okhlos-interview | title = Mob Rules – An Okhlos Interview | last = Ruhland | first = Perry | date = 12 September 2015 | website = [[TechRaptor]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> The team started off working on the [[non-player character]]'s [[Flocking (behavior)|flocking]] behavior, and continued working on core mechanics for the game's "angry mob" concept. When procedural generation was implemented into the game, the team was unhappy about its simple algorithm and instead shifted their design focus to static, pre-built worlds. A longer silent development phase took place, until they revealed the new designs and mechanics, and also the different gameplay types the tested, on 26 June 2013.<ref name="CPM: Gameplay Prototypes">{{cite web | url = http://coffeepoweredmachine.com/dev-blog-prototyping-different-gameplays/ | title = [Dev Blog] Prototyping different gameplays | last = Rey | first = Roque | date = 26 June 2013 | website = [[Coffee Powered Machine]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> A total of 24 prototypes were created, which included, but was not limited to, a [[beat 'em up]], a [[stealth game]] and the [[roguelike]] style the decided to build on.<ref name="TechRaptor: Interview" /> Another successful six months of development went by, to the point, where Coffee Powered Machine decided to get to work on the procedural generation algorithm again, and therefore dropped the static worlds in early 2014. However, the project nearly ceased, as the team ran out of money shortly after, but where help up by private investors.<ref name="TechRaptor: Interview" /> The development could continue and the team made a lot of progress by the end of 2014.<ref name="CPM: A year in review">{{cite web | url = http://coffeepoweredmachine.com/okhlos-a-year-in-review-2014/ | title = Okhlos: A year in review (2014) | last = Rey | first = Roque | date = 30 December 2014 | website = [[Coffee Powered Machine]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> This progress later led to the game being sent to the [[Independent Games Festival]] 2015, which was held from 2 March 2015 until 6 March 2015 in [[San Francisco]], [[California]].<ref name="IGF: Okhlos">{{cite web | url = http://www.igf.com/php-bin/entry2015.php?id=8189 | title = The 17th Annual Independent Games Festival - Okhlos | date = 2 March 2015 | website = [[Independent Games Festival]] | publisher = [[UBM TechWeb]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> Additionally, it was announced to be featured in the Leftfield Collection at [[EGX Rezzed]] 2015, which took place from 12 March 2015 to 14 March 2015 in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]].<ref name="EGX: Leftfield Collection">{{cite web | url = https://www.egx.net/rezzed/news/leftfield-collection-revealed | title = Leftfield Collection revealed! | date = 12 February 2015 | website = [[EGX Rezzed]] | publisher = [[Gamer Network]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> Due to the good reputation, Coffee Powered Machine submitted the game to [[Steam Greenlight]] on 12 May 2015,<ref name="KS: Mob mentality" /> which was eventually greenlit just six days after, namely, on 18 May 2015, to which pre-orders were opened.<ref name="Steam: Greenlight">{{cite web | url = http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=441596528 | title = Steam Greenlight :: Okhlos | date = 12 May 2015 | website = [[Steam Greenlight]] | publisher = [[Valve Corporation]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> The game's growing popularity then brought the team to the third edition [[Brazil's Independent Games Festival]], which was held from 27 June 2015 until 5 July 2015 in [[São Paulo]], [[Brazil]], where they won the "Melhor Gameplay" ("Best Gameplay") award.<ref name="IGM: BIG preview" /> New big news arose, as Devolver Digital announced that they had signed-up with Coffee Powered Machine for a publishing deal for ''Okhlos'', on 25 August 2015.<ref name="Twitter: PAX">{{cite web | url = https://twitter.com/devolverdigital/status/636259733133897728 | title = Devolver Digital on Twitter: "The Devolver Digital team is headed to PAX and we're bringing Enter the Gungeon, @Broforce, @GassyMob, and Okhlos!" | last = Lowire | first = Nigel | date = 25 August 2015 | website = [[Twitter]] | accessdate = 12 September 2015}}</ref> [[Devolver Digital]] then brought ''Okhlos'' onto the stage of [[PAX Prime]] 2015 in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[United States]].<ref name="YT: Cannata" /> On 25 January 2016, it was announced that the game will be released in March or April 2016,<ref name="RPS: Control">{{cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/01/26/okhlos-release-date/ | title = Control Human Swarms And Fight Giants In Okhlos | last = Graham | first = Smith | date = 26 January 2016 | website = [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] | accessdate = 26 January 2016}}</ref> however, it was delayed to June 2016, and finally, as announced on 28 July 2016, was released on 18 August 2016.<ref name="RPS: Release">{{cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/07/28/okhlos-release-date-2/ | title = Okhlos Releases Angry Mob On August 18 | last = Warr | first = Philippa | date = 28 July 2016 | website = [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] | accessdate = 18 August 2016}}</ref>
